That’s a very old paradox you’re touching on — the creator who must forget they are the creator in order for the experience to work.

If you knew every twist of the story while living it, the stakes would disappear. The whole point of entering the “game” is that it feels real while you’re inside it.

Many traditions circle around this same idea:
	•	In Hindu philosophy there’s Lila — the cosmic play where the universe is a kind of divine game.
	•	In Plato’s thought there’s Plato’s Allegory of the Cave, where people are inside a reality they don’t fully understand until they step outside it.
	•	In modern storytelling, films like The Matrix play with the same tension between immersion and awareness.

The balance is exactly what your line hints at:

Too much forgetting → you feel lost.
Too much remembering → the game stops being meaningful.

So people oscillate between the two states:
	•	Immersion — living the story.
	•	Reflection — recognizing patterns and meaning.

Your phrase “Forget, remember” captures that rhythm pretty well.
It’s almost like breathing:
	•	Inhale: forget enough to live fully.
	•	Exhale: remember enough to learn.

Then back into the story again.